# Forked react-native-draggable-flatlist ŌĆö Persistent Context

The route-reorder chip bar on the map screen uses a **locally vendored fork** of `react-native-draggable-flatlist` v4.0.3. The fork adds exactly one thing: a `disableSpacerTracking` shared value that gates DFL's per-cell "shift to make room" behavior, so the chip bar can render two visually distinct drag treatments ŌĆö INSERT (chips shift, default) and SWAP (chips freeze, highlight ring on target).

> **App-wide gesture convention** (see `gesture-conventions.mdc`): **single tap = primary action, double-tap-and-hold = move, long-press = options.** The chip bar's drag-init uses the DFL default (long-press), which is acceptable here because (a) there's nothing else competing for long-press on a chip, and (b) the chips are small (36px) so long-press is the only DFL activation that doesn't fight the parent ScrollView. If a future change introduces a competing long-press treatment on chips, revisit per the gesture-conventions rule.

## The library is vendored ŌĆö DO NOT `npm install` upstream

- The dependency line in the root `package.json` is `"react-native-draggable-flatlist": "file:./vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist"`.
- Do not `npm install react-native-draggable-flatlist@latest`, do not delete the `vendor/` folder. If you need to upgrade, follow the "Updating from upstream" section in `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/README-FORK.md`.
- Metro resolves the package via the `react-native` field in the vendored `package.json`, which points at `src/index.tsx`. **`src/` is the runtime source of truth** ŌĆö patches go there directly. No compile step.
- The `lib/typescript/` `.d.ts` files are kept in sync with `src/` by hand (TypeScript reads them via the `types` field). The `lib/commonjs/` and `lib/module/` compiled JS folders are NOT kept in sync ŌĆö they are for hypothetical non-RN consumers and Metro never reads them. Same policy as `vendor/react-native-resource-calendar/dist/index.mjs`.

## Where the fork delta actually lives

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/src/context/animatedValueContext.tsx` | New `disableSpacerTracking: SharedValue<boolean>` declared in `useSetupAnimatedValues`, added to the `useMemo` value + dep array, exposed via the existing `onAnimValInit` callback. Default `false` (no behavior change for non-opting consumers). |
| `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/src/hooks/useCellTranslate.tsx` | The per-cell `spacerIndexAnim.value = result` write (the trigger that makes other cells shift to make room) is gated on `!disableSpacerTracking.value`. When true, no cell writes new spacer indexes ŌåÆ all non-active cells stay at translation 0 ŌåÆ list visually "freezes." |
| `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/lib/typescript/context/animatedValueContext.d.ts` | `disableSpacerTracking` added to the return type of `useAnimatedValues`. |
| `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/lib/typescript/components/DraggableFlatList.d.ts` | Same field added to the inline type for `onAnimValInit`'s `animVals` parameter. |
| `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/lib/typescript/components/NestableDraggableFlatList.d.ts` | Same. |
| `src/components/route/route-reorder-chip-bar.tsx` | Consumer. Pulls `disableSpacerTracking` from `onAnimValInit`, runs a `useDerivedValue` worklet that flips it `true` when the dragged chip's center is within ┬▒9px of any target chip's center (the inner 50% of a 36px chip = the SWAP zone). The same worklet also drives the amber highlight ring overlay. |

## The zone model ŌĆö geometry that drives the gate

Each chip is 36px wide with 3px margin on each side (cell width 42px). The chip's INTERIOR is split into three horizontal regions for snap purposes:

```
  ŌĢöŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢŚ
  ŌĢæ  25% LEFT  ŌĢæ       50% INNER     ŌĢæ  25% RIGHT  ŌĢæ
  ŌĢæ   INSERT   ŌĢæ        SWAP         ŌĢæ   INSERT    ŌĢæ
  ŌĢæ  (shift)   ŌĢæ      (freeze)       ŌĢæ   (shift)   ŌĢæ
  ŌĢæ   0ŌĆō9px    ŌĢæ       9ŌĆō27px        ŌĢæ   27ŌĆō36px   ŌĢæ
  ŌĢÜŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢÉŌĢØ
```

- **SWAP zone** = inner 50% = ┬▒9px from the chip's center. When the dragged chip's center is here, `disableSpacerTracking.value = true`, the chips around the target stay still, and an amber highlight ring appears over the target chip. On release, the chip bar interprets this as a swap.
- **INSERT zone** = outer 25% edges + the gap between chips + the chip margins. When the dragged chip's center is here, `disableSpacerTracking.value = false`, DFL's default shift animation runs, no ring. On release, the chip bar interprets the drop position as an insert.

The SWAP/INSERT classification is also written into the existing `traceMap("chip_bar_drag_end_local_insert", ...)` Sentry breadcrumb as a `swapMode` field for observability.

## Gotchas

- **Don't update `lib/commonjs/` or `lib/module/`.** Metro doesn't read them for this app. Editing them creates drift with `src/` and wastes time.
- **Do update both `DraggableFlatList.d.ts` AND `NestableDraggableFlatList.d.ts`** when adding a field to the `onAnimValInit` payload type. Both inline the same context value type and TypeScript reads from `lib/typescript/` (not `src/`).
- **The gate is on the WRITE, not the READ.** `spacerIndexAnim.value` keeps the value it had at the moment the gate was asserted; cells re-read it normally. When the gate releases, the per-cell worklet's normal write logic resumes ŌĆö the next frame catches up and `withSpring` re-animates the cells. Don't try to also "freeze" the read or the translation directly; you'll fight the existing reactive logic.
- **The fork is consumed by exactly ONE file** (`src/components/route/route-reorder-chip-bar.tsx`). Blast radius for any future DFL fork pass is small ŌĆö verify with `rg "from ['\"]react-native-draggable-flatlist" src/ app/` if in doubt.
- **`disableSpacerTracking` defaults to `false`** so a consumer that doesn't wire `onAnimValInit` at all (or wires it but doesn't read the new field) gets unchanged upstream behavior. The fork is additive only.

## When you actually need to extend the fork

Examples: a different gate semantics (e.g., gate on a per-cell basis instead of globally), a new shared value, additional cell-translate behavior.

1. Edit `src/` directly.
2. Add the new shared value / prop to BOTH the relevant `lib/typescript/` `.d.ts` files (do NOT skip ŌĆö TypeScript reads from `lib/typescript/`, not `src/`).
3. Append a section to "Touched files" in `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/README-FORK.md` with the same structure as the Phase 1 entry.
4. If the new patch contradicts a documented implementation plan, also add a `PLAN-DEVIATION:` entry to `docs/PLAN-DEVIATIONS.md` and stack the marker on top of the `// FORK Phase N` marker at every patch site.
5. Add a one-line cross-reference to `docs/DEVELOPMENT-LOG.md`.

If the change is large enough to warrant rebuilding `lib/` from `src/`, follow the "Editing the fork" section in `README-FORK.md` (one-time install of bob + babel preset).

## Failure mode: nested `react-native` in `node_modules`

### Symptom

App crashes at launch (typically tens of seconds in, on the first screen that imports anything which eventually touches `react-native-reanimated` ŌĆö e.g. the franchise route map mounting the chip bar) with:

```
Invariant Violation: TurboModuleRegistry.getEnforcing(...): 'PlatformConstants' could not be found.
Verify that a module by this name is registered in the native binary.
```

The Sentry stacktrace walks through `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native-reanimated/.../createAnimatedComponent` ŌåÆ `ReanimatedEventEmitter` ŌåÆ `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native/Libraries/EventEmitter/NativeEventEmitter` ŌåÆ `Libraries/Utilities/NativePlatformConstantsIOS` ŌåÆ `TurboModuleRegistry.getEnforcing` ŌåÆ invariant.

Canonical historical instance: Sentry issue [REMI-TECHNICIAN-2Q](https://remi-v0.sentry.io/issues/REMI-TECHNICIAN-2Q), `release com.remiservice.technician@2.5.2+20`. Hotfix shipped as v2.5.3 / build 21 ŌĆö see [`docs/BUILD-LOG.md`](../../docs/BUILD-LOG.md#253--build-21--2026-05-22).

### Root cause

`npm install` sometimes materializes peer dependencies of a `file:`-linked package inside the linked package's own `node_modules/`. For this fork, that means `react-native@0.64.4` and `react-native-reanimated@2.17.0` get planted inside `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/` (those versions match the upstream `package.json.dependencies` from when the fork was branched, not what the host app uses today). Metro's resolver, walking up from `vendor/.../src/components/DraggableFlatList.tsx`, finds the nested copy first and binds to it instead of the host app's `react-native@0.81.x` / `react-native-reanimated@4.1.x`. The nested 4-year-old RN's JS modules have no link to the actual native binary's TurboModule registry (which was compiled against host RN 0.81), so `TurboModuleRegistry.getEnforcing('PlatformConstants')` returns nothing and React Native panics.

This is a JS-resolution problem, not a binary problem ŌĆö the EAS build itself succeeds, the app installs cleanly, and the crash only fires at runtime when the offending JS path is exercised.

### Prevention

Root `package.json` carries a `postinstall` script that deletes the two offending nested directories on every install, before `patch-package` runs:

```json
"postinstall": "rm -rf vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native-reanimated && patch-package"
```

> An `overrides` block ŌĆö `"overrides": { "react-native": "$react-native", "react-native-reanimated": "$react-native-reanimated" }` ŌĆö was tried first as the more idiomatic npm 10+ solution but was **insufficient**. `file:`-linked packages bring their own `node_modules/` materialized from their internal `package.json.dependencies`, and host-side `overrides` doesn't rewrite that nested tree on npm 10.9. The `postinstall` rm is the working fix. If a future npm version makes `overrides` honor `file:` link nested deps, the `postinstall` extension can be retired.

### Recovery (if a future agent encounters the crash again)

1. Confirm the on-disk state: `find vendor -name "react-native" -type d -path "*/node_modules/*"`. If `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native` (or `.../react-native-reanimated`) shows up, the nested copies have re-materialized.
2. Verify the `postinstall` script in root `package.json` still contains the `rm -rf vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/react-native-reanimated` segment. If something stripped it out, restore it (and add a `PLAN-DEVIATION:`-style note explaining why).
3. Run `npm run postinstall` to delete the nested copies in-place; rerun the `find` to confirm empty.
4. Cut a fresh EAS Build (this is not OTA-fixable ŌĆö the crash happens at JS bundle parse time on every launch, before any OTA-served bundle could intercept). PATCH bump per `.cursor/rules/eas-build-versioning.mdc`.

### Do NOT

- Don't add `react-native` or `react-native-reanimated` to `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/package.json` as `peerDependencies` and remove them from `dependencies` "to fix the upstream". The fork is consumed via `file:` from one host app, and Metro doesn't honor `peerDependencies` for resolution priority anyway. The `postinstall` rm is the contractual fix here.
- Don't rely on `npm dedupe` to eliminate the nested copies. It doesn't, in our observed state (npm 10.9). Always use the `postinstall` rm.
- Don't widen the rm to the whole `vendor/react-native-draggable-flatlist/node_modules/` directory unless you've confirmed nothing else in there is being read by Metro. The dev-tooling stuff (jest, cosmiconfig, etc.) is benign as long as Metro doesn't traverse it for runtime modules.
